# spring-core-handson — Hands-on 4: Load Country from Spring XML

A plain Spring Core (no Spring Boot, no web) exercise: read a `Country`
bean out of an XML-configured `ApplicationContext` and print it.

This is a **separate project** from `spring-learn` (the REST service you
built earlier) — kept apart deliberately so its `Country` class
(`com.cognizant.springlearn.Country`) and its `country.xml` (a Spring
*bean* config file) don't collide with the REST project's
`com.cognizant.springlearn.model.Country` and its `country.xml` (a
plain *data* file).

## Project structure

```
spring-core-handson/
├── pom.xml
├── src/main/java/com/cognizant/springlearn/
│   ├── Country.java
│   └── SpringLearnApplication.java
└── src/main/resources/
    ├── country.xml     (Spring bean definition for "country")
    └── logback.xml     (enables DEBUG logging so you can see the calls)
```

## How to run in VS Code

1. Unzip and open the `spring-core-handson` folder.
2. Let the Java extensions index the Maven project (needs the
   "Extension Pack for Java").
3. Open `SpringLearnApplication.java` and click **Run** above `main()`,
   or from a terminal:
   ```bash
   cd spring-core-handson
   mvn compile exec:java -Dexec.mainClass=com.cognizant.springlearn.SpringLearnApplication
   ```
   (or `mvn package` then `java -jar target/spring-core-handson.jar`)

## Expected console output

```
... DEBUG com.cognizant.springlearn.Country - Inside Country Constructor.
... DEBUG com.cognizant.springlearn.Country - Inside setCode(). Setting code to: IN
... DEBUG com.cognizant.springlearn.Country - Inside setName(). Setting name to: India
... DEBUG com.cognizant.springlearn.SpringLearnApplication - Country : Country [code=IN, name=India]
```

Notice the **order**: the no-arg constructor runs first, *then* the
setters — this is exactly how Spring builds a bean from `<property>`
tags (see the SME notes on `context.getBean()` below).
